The calling signal is a short phrase usually lasting for approximately 1.5–4 s (
Figs. 44–61
). It begins with a short succession of 3–10 high-amplitude pulses separated by distinct gaps. Occasionally, the phrase is preceded by additional pulses separated by longer gaps (
Figs. 49–51
). The main part of a phrase is a succession of partially merged pulses following each other at a rate of about 50–55/s at a temperature 21 
oC
and 75–85/s at 30–33 
oC
. This part of the signal usually (but not always) has much lower amplitude and sometimes is hardly visible on the oscillograms (
Fig. 59
). Single males as a rule produce up to three phrases separated by short pauses and then become silent for a long time (
Fig. 46
). Very rarely do they produce several phrases almost without gaps; such phrases are much shorter than single ones (
Figs. 52, 60–61
). Two nearby males usually sing alternately (
Figs. 50–51
). Signals of males from different localities do not have significant differences.
